node.text:
The “scoop marks” are widely present at the oldest megalithic sites scattered throughout the world.
_

From Egypt to South America, these marks can be seen at Macchu Picchu, Ollantaytambo, the Aswan Quarry, the three main pyramids at Giza on the casing stones and granite blocks scattered in their vicinity, but also Stonehenge and other megalithic sites in England.
_

The process that was used to craft these stones and that left the scoop marks on them is matter of debate and a still unexplained topic.
_

The main hypothesis laid out by Egyptologists is that the marks at the Aswan Quarry were left as a result of pounding the granite with diorite balls.
_

Not only this process would be incredibly slow, but it also wouldn’t have left symmetrical and even marks.
_

The tight space flanking the unfinished obelisk would’ve left no maneuvering space to perform such technique.
_

Moreover, the marks go from the side of the obelisk but they also stretch under it (Pic.2), making it practically impossible to achieve by pounding.
_

The marks are also present on top of the obelisk itself (Pic.3).
_

Diorite is also almost the same hardness than granite on the Mohs Scale, making the alleged process extremely hard to be performed at this level.
_

The sophistication at Aswan and throughout ancient Egyptian megalithic sites is such that it’s quite naive to imagine them bashing against granite with diorite balls.
_

Even the Wikipedia page reads as follows: “Modern Egyptian suggests the use of diorite balls as carving tools for granite, at Aswan; a frequently repeated but scientifically unproven method”.
_

Technique aside, the real enigma is how and why the civilizations of England and South America knew this exact process. 
_

Going back in time trying to figure out how old this process might be things get even more baffling, as the scoop marks can be spotted at 12.000 years old Gobekli Tepe in Turkey on top of the famous T-shaped pillars (pic.4).
